                <head>332. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On October 27, General <persName corresp="#p_AKM1">Ayub Khan</persName> assumed
                    the office of President of Pakistan, following <persName corresp="#p_MMGI1"
                        >Mirza</persName>’s resignation. The Embassy reported this development to
                    the Department of State in telegram 1029 from Karachi, October 28. (Department
                    of State, Central Files, 790D.00/10–2858)</p>
                <p>At the 384th meeting of the National Security Council on October 30, <persName
                        corresp="#p_DAW1">Allen Dulles</persName> discussed the political changes in
                    Pakistan during his survey of significant world developments affecting U.S.
                    security: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Mr. <persName corresp="#p_DAW1">Dulles</persName> stated that the
                            take-over in Pakistan by the Chief of Staff, General <persName
                                corresp="#p_AKM1">Ayub</persName>, could be considered the logical
                            result of the coup d’etat which had taken place earlier. <persName
                                corresp="#p_AKM1">Ayub</persName>’s assumption of complete power was
                            likely to improve the situation generally in the country. The only real
                            problem would be East Pakistan, which will not be very happy at the
                            prospect of military rule from West Pakistan.” (Memorandum of discussion
                            by <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Gleason</persName>, October 31;
                            Eisenhower Library, Whitman File, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                            Records)</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
            </div>
